<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: DOT spells and exp loss</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?Stupid">Stupid</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 2:46 p.m. 7/5/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: DOT spells and exp loss<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=2008" TARGET=_self>Major Question on DOT plz answer! (text)</A> (Meteo)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>> Are diseases and poisons (which are a side effect of almost all

<BR>&gt; the good necro spelld) illegal?
<P>&gt; And, if so, WHY???
<P>All DOT (Damage Over Time) spells are affected. What happens is this:
<P>Say you cast a DOT spell on another player. Now if you kill them quickly, nothing happens (other than them dying).
<P>But most people tend to hang out near zone boundaries. I do it, you do it, we all do it to some extent or another. So when you are losing a fight, experience has taught us to run for the zone boundary to escape. Against NPCs and monsters, this works. But it is actually silly when you are fighting another player, since they will just follow you into the new zone - but there you have it. When you cross into the new zone, the DOT spell "loses" it's owner. Just like you can't bring summoned items, pets, and whatnot across a zone boundary. The DOT spell is then no longer a player-cast spell, but is now part of the game world -- just as if it had been cast by a casting NPC. Thus, if the unlucky recipient of the DOT spell then dies due to the effect of the spell, he is considered having been killed by a NPC and <u>not</u> another player. And takes a exp loss accordingly.
<P>So, if you get a DOT spell cast on you in combat, you have two choices: stay in the zone you are in until it wears off (and risk getting killed and looted by the caster), or zone and attempt to escape (and risk taking a exp loss if/when you die from the DOT).
<P>Thus spake Verant.
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
